ine, Fife, Skotland, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotland, United Kingdom","Hungary":"Ungarn"},"nl":{"1018–1067":"1018–1067","1016–1057":"1016–1057","1044–1093":"1044–1093","1045–1093":"1045–1093","1051–1126":"1051–1126","0975–1038":"0975–1038","0985–1060":"0985–1060","about 1051":"circa 1051","8 September 1045":"8 september 1045","1044":"1044","1051":"1051","1060":"1060","1093":"1093","0985":"0985","1018":"1018","0975":"0975","1038":"1038","1126":"1126","1016":"1016","1057":"1057","1067":"1067","1045":"1045","19 April 1057":"19 april 1057","15 aug 1038":"15 augustus 1038","about 1044":"circa 1044","Mecsekndasd, Baranya, Hungary":"Baranya, Hongarije","Dunfermline abbey":"Dunfermline Abbey, Dunfermline, Fife, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hungary":"Hongarije"},"en":{"1018–1067":"1018–1067","1016–1057":"1016–1057","1044–1093":"1044–1093","1045–1093":"1045–1093","1051–1126":"1051–1126","0975–1038":"0975–1038","0985–1060":"0985–1060","about 1051":"about 1051","8 September 1045":"8 September 1045","1044":"1044","1051":"1051","1060":"1060","1093":"1093","0985":"0985","1018":"1018","0975":"0975","1038":"1038","1126":"1126","1016":"1016","1057":"1057","1067":"1067","1045":"1045","19 April 1057":"19 April 1057","15 aug 1038":"15 August 1038","about 1044":"about 1044","Mecsekndasd, Baranya, Hungary":"Baranya, Hungary","Dunfermline abbey":"Dunfermline Abbey, Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Hungary":"Hungary","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Brunswick","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the city in Saxony now known in German as Braunschweig (see 2 below). This name is associated (especially in the 18th century) with the royal House of Hanover, who brought it to England. It is now more common in the US than in Britain.","German: habitational name from Low German <i>Brunswick</i>, the original name (a compound of <i>Bruns</i> + <i>wik</i> ‘Bruno's settlement’). The standard German form of the name was adopted in 1573."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Wessex","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Messick   1, a surname of unclear French origin.","History: Bearers of the surname <i>Messex</i> are descendants of Julian Messick from France (see   Messick  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Messick","meanings":["Americanized form of an unidentified French surname, presumably <b>Messac</b>: habitational name from any of several places with this name (e.g. in Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany), named in Gallo-Roman times as the estate of someone called <i>Mettius</i>. Compare   Messex   and   Mezick  .","In some cases an Americanized form of Croatian (and possibly also Bosniak) <b>Mesić</b> and <b>Mešić</b>, Slovenian <b>Mešič</b> (see   Mesic  , compare   Mesick   2).","In some cases an Americanized form of Slovak <b>Mesík</b>: unexplained. Compare   Mesick   3."]}]},{"name":"Agatha","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Agnes   and   Agatha ."],"variants":[{"name":"Agnes","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Princess Agatha Von Brunswick Of Wessex was born in 1018, her father, Saint Stephen I of Hungary, was 43 and her mother, Gisela von Bayern, was 33. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Edward Ætheling the Exile. She died in 1067, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 49, and was buried in Dunfermline Abbey, Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1018–1067":"1018–1067","1016–1057":"1016–1057","1044–1093":"1044–1093","1045–1093":"1045–1093","1051–1126":"1051–1126","0975–1038":"0975–1038","0985–1060":"0985–1060","about 1051":"umbes 1051","8 September 1045":"8. september 1045","1044":"1044","1051":"1051","1060":"1060","1093":"1093","0985":"0985","1018":"1018","0975":"0975","1038":"1038","1126":"1126","1016":"1016","1057":"1057","1067":"1067","1045":"1045","19 April 1057":"19. aprill 1057","15 aug 1038":"15. august 1038","about 1044":"umbes 1044","Mecsekndasd, Baranya, Hungary":"Baranya, Ungari","Dunfermline abbey":"Dunfermline Abbey, Dunfermline, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Hungary":"Ungari"},"fi":{"1018–1067":"1018–1067","1016–1057":"1016–1057","1044–1093":"1044–1093","1045–1093":"1045–1093","1051–1126":"1051–1126","0975–1038":"0975–1038","0985–1060":"0985–1060","about 1051":"noin 1051","8 September 1045":"8. syyskuuta 1045","1044":"1044","1051":"1051","1060":"1060","1093":"1093","0985":"0985","1018":"1018","0975":"0975","1038":"1038","1126":"1126","1016":"1016","1057":"1057","1067":"1067","1045":"1045","19 April 1057":"19. huhtikuuta 1057","15 aug 1038":"15. elokuuta 1038","about 1044":"noin 1044","Mecsekndasd, Baranya, Hungary":"Baranya, Unkari","Dunfermline abbey":"Dunfermline Abbey, Dunfermline, Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hungary":"Unkari"},"fr":{"1018–1067":"1018–1067","1016–1057":"1016–1057","1044–1093":"1044–1093","1045–1093":"1045–1093","1